## 4. Pattern investigation (Team Member 1 perspective)

Even though deeper analysis is mainly for Team Member 3, I still looked at the sequences to see if anything obvious stood out.

A few things I noticed:

- Some questions have a lot of "1" answers across respondents.
- Some questions have many zeros (unanswered), especially near the end.
- The distribution of answers doesn't look random at first glance.
- There might be a repeating structure, but it's not clear from one file alone.

Since my role is mainly parsing, I didn’t run full statistical tests, but I made sure the data I produce is clean so the analysis module can detect any patterns properly.

## 5. Assumptions and limitations

### Assumptions
- Each question block contains exactly four answer lines.
- `[x]` always marks the selected answer.
- The dataset follows the same structure for all respondents.

### Limitations
- If a file is formatted incorrectly, the function will raise an error.
- The parser does not attempt to fix corrupted files.
- It assumes the dataset always contains 100 questions.

These limitations are acceptable because the dataset is controlled and provided by the module staff.

## 6. Reflection

This module was more challenging than I expected because the raw text files are not in a simple CSV format. I had to carefully detect the `[x]` markers and make sure the parser didn’t get confused by blank lines or question text.

I also learned how important it is to write clean, well‑documented code because the rest of the team depends on my output. If my module is wrong, every other module breaks.

Overall, I’m confident that my implementation is correct, robust, and easy for the rest of the group to use.

